ert</i>, a hybrid of Old Norse <i>Thorr</i> ‘Thor’, the name of the god of thunder, + ancient Germanic <i>-berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was probably formed on the Continent; see   Turberville  .","perhaps in some cases a nickname from Old French and Middle English <i>turbot</i>, <i>turbut</i> ‘turbot’, for someone who caught or sold or resembled this fish."]},{"name":"Turbyfill","meanings":["Altered form of English   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Tuberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Turville","meanings":["English (Surrey and Hampshire; of Norman origin):","habitational name from Tourville‐la‐Campagne (Eure, France). The placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Thórr</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘farmstead, estate’ (from Latin <i>villa</i>).","occasionally a shortened form of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Turbeville","meanings":["English: variant of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Troublefield","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Turberville  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Turberville was born 